76 2021-01-16 injection site redness, injection site pruritus, injection site rash, injection site swelling, injection site warmth Observations Covid19 vaccine: On 1/8/21 the first of the 2-stage Moderna vaccine was injected at the... Read more
Close
Observations Covid19 vaccine: On 1/8/21 the first of the 2-stage Moderna vaccine was injected at the facility. The injection was barely felt and the symptoms were mild over the next few days. On January 17th - 9 days later - the area around the injection felt itchy upon waking. Swelling, redness and heat were observed at the injection site in an area about 2 1/2 inches in diameter. Soap and water was applied for the itchiness and Tylenol was taken. The itchiness mostly subsided. Above the affected area a few scattered raised splotches are present. I had read about this set of reactions to the vaccine but had not read that this might occur as many as 9 days after the initial shot, so I thought I'd share that with my doctor via My Chart and with you in case it was useful. Thanks. This is the first day of the reaction and I expect it to go away on its own over the next few days. It's not sore just slightly itchy.

COVID-19 Vaccine EUA Ten days after the injection of Covid 19 injection my arm swelled up, and became very red and itchy at the site of the injection. It just came up out of nowhere it seems as I had no reaction at all to the vaccine during the prior 10 days since the vaccination. This continued for two days. The first day after it happened I felt tired and weak in the morning. I got into work here at the house and the weakness went away. I treated the itchy situation with Clobetasol Propionate Cream which I had here and was prescribed by my dermatologist for poison ivy. That took away the itchy situation that was very annoying. Two days into it the swelling began to go down. Today is the 4th day since the problem occurred and there is no swelling and only a slight redness. I am assuming that I can take injection #2 on February 9 as scheduled.

Close
On February 14, I had used the handlebar rotation exercise of a stationery bike for 5 minutes. The next day I noticed a large swelling about the size of half a pear on the muscle where my Moderna injection was done. It was as hard as a nut, red, and warm and itchy with a red rash around it. I saw an urgent care medical person and was told it was probably a reaction to the exercise and that sometimes that happens after an injection. I was told to use cold compresses, hydrocortison cream, and rest it. I did this, for 5 days, but though the swelling subsided, the rash continued to move around and down my arm. I went back to urgent care on February 19 and was told that it looked better. I was offered prednazone for it, but declined since I was still on Budesonide . I was told it would probably clear up over the weekend. On February 22 it hadn't cleared up so I saw a PC. She noted the rash had spread, but swelling had gone down. She checked my lymph node under my left arm and noticed it was swollen. She said it was most likely due to a mild infection in the arm where I had received the vaccination. She prescribed a Zpack and after 2 days, all symptoms were gone and I felt so much better. This event happened 10 days after my vaccination.

I received my injection on 1/25/2021 I had my second COVID shot, everything went well, I just had a little pain and swelling and was fine. About 7 hours later i got up from chair and i was dizzy and my balance was off and i almost fell into table. I didn't feel right. I went and sat back down and i was very tired and i started getting headache. I called my daughter and a nurse she knows told me to take extra strength Tylenol 500 mg take 2 every 6 hours. I started at 730 and went until 130. I slept on and off and got up Tuesday and my arm was still hurting. I was very tired and had no energy. When i got up later in the afternoon i had extreme chills. It was 83 degrees in Florida nd i turned heat up to 84 and i was still shaking. I got under covers and had a fever it was 100.8. Went to sleep that night and fever broke. Got up Wednesday and felt a little better, still had headache and tired. Decided to take a shower. I noticed my left arm where the injection was was all red. 6-7 inches long and about 5 inches wide which i never saw before. after shower I called my PCP I contacted the nurse said she thought it was normal and if there was no change to call her back on Friday. my arm is still red and warm i went to sleep but couldn't sleep. I saw an article about COVID arm rash seen after Modern vaccine and now i know that's what I had. I feel better after I read it in the magazine today and it said it will only last a week. This should be listed as a side effect so nobody else wonders what it is. I drank so much water because it said to drink plenty of water and i tried to use arm as much as possible.

On 05 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot #: 039K20A) (route of administration not specified) in the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 17 Jan 2021, 12 to 13 days after the vaccination, the patient developed hives on inner arms which would come and go, appearing in the morning and disappearing during daytime. Patient took Benadryl for it and applied cortisone cream. On 26 Jan 2021, after taking a walk, the patient experienced weakness, slight dizziness, and nausea. Patient was taken to the emergency room (ER) and vomited. The patient was sent home the same day but the patient's blood pressure was noted to be fluctuating. On 27 Jan 2021, the patient "felt that she was going to die" and had general malaise. The patient was brought to the ER of another hospital but again was sent home. On 29 Jan 2021, with the symptoms still ongoing and a red streak noted on the inner side of the left arm, the patient was admitted for observation at the second hospital. Laboratory details included Blood works and radiologic tests were done with normal results. The patient's blood pressure was stabilized but patient was still experiencing malaise and still had the on and off rash on both inner arms. Treatment information included Benadryl and Cortisone Cream for the indication hives. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The event, blood pressure fluctuation, was considered resolved/recovered on 01 Feb 2021. The outcome of the events, hives on inner arms, red streak on inner side of left arm, weakness, dizziness, nausea, vomited, felt was going to die and general malaise, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Further information has been requested. This case concerns an 83-year-old female hospitalized with serious unexpected malaise, erythema, anxiety, and NS unexpected urticaria, asthenia, dizziness, BP fluctuation and NS expected nausea, vomiting. Event onset 23 days after the first dose of mRNA-1273. BP changes resolved, other events unknown. As above, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

some bruising near my eye; area was a little tender; Afib started to act up; blacked out; Hit forehead on the door jamb; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer who was a 84-years-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced area was a little tender, Afib started to act up, blacked out, hit forehead on the door jamb and had some bruising near eye. The patient's medical history, as provided by the reporter, included atrial fibrillation with premature ventricular contractions (PVCs), and three cardioversions in the past 30 years. Concomitant medications reported included metoprolol, alprazolam, apixaban, amlodipine besylate, telmisartan, atorvastatin, ubidecarenone, multivitamin, vitamin B2, fish oil and cranberry extract. On 14 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly in the left deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 14 Jan 2021, after receiving the vaccine, the patient had no pain or soreness, but the area was a little tender if you pushed, and she waited one hour in the hospital afterwards. As the patient was getting ready to leave, she felt a little lightheaded. She was driven home, she ate lunch and then worked in the yard for a little bit. As she came inside, her Afib started to act up, she took an extra half of metoprolol, and had supper. She took half an alprazolam before going to bed. That night, as she got up to use the restroom, she had a strange feeling in her head like everything was going away. As she walked into the hallway, she blacked out and hit her forehead on the door jamb. Her forehead was all right but there was some bruising near her eye. She went back to bed and fell asleep. On Friday, February 18th, 2021, patient received Moderna COVID-19 vaccine in the left deltoid administered by Pharm D at our pharmacy. The patient called the pharmacy on March 4th, 2021 to explain that her arm was red and itchy. The pharmacist that day told the patient to use ice compresses and to come by the pharmacy to show us her reaction. Today, March 5th, the patient came to the pharmacy with her son to show us her left deltoid. I observed her arm was red and hot to the touch. She has very defined edges of the rash on her arm. She did not have streaking on her arm, that I observed. Patient said she had a small, red spot about 3 days after she received the shot, which started February 21st . She was complaining of itching and has been watching the red spot get bigger every day. I instructed her to call you to have you look at her arm. She said it was just itching and she would like to try OTC products before going to the doctor. I instructed her to take Benadryl 25mg up to four times per day. Because Benadryl will make her tired, she can only take it when she is at home and not driving. I also gave her Hydrocortisone 1% ointment to use at least twice per day on her arm. I also reiterated that ice packs would help with the redness and discomfort. She verbalized her understanding. I instructed her to call you to make an appointment if she is not improving. I also told her if she sees any signs of continued spreading or red streaks on her arm, she needs to seek immediate medical attention.

Patient verbally reported to me that about 4 hours after the shot, she began experiencing severe shocks all over her face and into her left neck and chest area. This quickly worsened to include her left arm. That all resolved after a nap. But when she woke up, and went to the mirror, she noted that her left face was slow and drooping. She went to the ER. It was noted that she was having a severe problem with swallowing. She also was noting severe pain in left external ear canal. She had obvious severe breakout in the left ear canal - and the immediate area. She was sent home - and came to my office the next day. By that time, the symptoms had become much much worse. She was unable to swallow. The outbreak in the left ear was much more pronounced. And her entire left face and left tongue were paralyzed. She was diagnosed with the Ramsay-Hunt Syndrome - she was unable to talk or swallow. She was readmitted back into the hospital.
